Q. When would you use shared_ptr and when would you use unique_ptr explain with example
In modern C++, **`std::unique_ptr`** and **`std::shared_ptr`** are smart pointers that implement **RAII** to manage dynamic resources safely.  
The key difference between them is **ownership semantics**.

***

# 1. `std::unique_ptr`

## What it means

✅ **Exclusive ownership**  
Only **one** `unique_ptr` can own the object at a time.

*   Cannot be copied
*   Can be **moved**
*   Lightweight (no reference counting)

***

## When to use `unique_ptr`

Use `unique_ptr` when:

✅ There is **one clear owner**  
✅ You want **maximum performance**  
✅ Ownership can be **transferred**, but not shared  
✅ You want the **default choice**

> **Rule of thumb:**  
> *If you don’t explicitly need shared ownership, use `unique_ptr`.*

***

## Example: Single Ownership

```cpp
#include <memory>

class File {
public:
    File() { /* open file */ }
    ~File() { /* close file */ }
};

void process() {
    std::unique_ptr<File> f = std::make_unique<File>();
    // f owns the File object
} // f goes out of scope → File destroyed
```

✅ Deterministic cleanup  
✅ No overhead

***

## Transferring Ownership

```cpp
std::unique_ptr<File> createFile() {
    return std::make_unique<File>();  // moved automatically
}

int main() {
    auto f = createFile();  // ownership transferred
}
```

Still only **one owner** at any time.

***

# 2. `std::shared_ptr`

## What it means

✅ **Shared ownership**  
Multiple `shared_ptr`s can point to the **same object**.

*   Uses **reference counting**
*   Object destroyed when **last owner releases**
*   Slight runtime overhead

***

## When to use `shared_ptr`

Use `shared_ptr` when:

✅ Multiple parts of the program **need to share ownership**  
✅ Object lifetime is **not tied to a single scope**  
✅ Ownership is **unclear or distributed**

> `shared_ptr` models “**we all own this object together**”.

***

## Example: Shared Ownership

```cpp
#include <memory>

class Logger {
public:
    void log(const std::string& msg) {}
};

void serviceA(std::shared_ptr<Logger> logger) {
    logger->log("From A");
}

void serviceB(std::shared_ptr<Logger> logger) {
    logger->log("From B");
}

int main() {
    auto logger = std::make_shared<Logger>();

    serviceA(logger);
    serviceB(logger);
} // Logger destroyed when last shared_ptr goes out of scope
```

✅ Logger survives as long as **any service uses it**

***

## Reference Counting Concept

```cpp
auto p1 = std::make_shared<int>(10); // count = 1
auto p2 = p1;                        // count = 2
p1.reset();                          // count = 1
p2.reset();                          // count = 0 → object destroyed
```

***

# 3. Key Differences Summary

| Feature        | `unique_ptr` | `shared_ptr`       |
| -------------- | ------------ | ------------------ |
| Ownership      | Exclusive    | Shared             |
| Copyable       | ❌ No         | ✅ Yes              |
| Movable        | ✅ Yes        | ✅ Yes              |
| Overhead       | Very low     | Higher (ref count) |
| Lifetime       | Scope-based  | Reference-based    |
| Default choice | ✅ Yes        | ❌ Only when needed |

***

# 4. Real‑World Analogy

### `unique_ptr`

🏠 **House with one owner**  
You can sell it (move ownership), but only one person owns it at a time.

### `shared_ptr`

🏢 **Joint bank account**  
Account exists as long as **at least one person** is using it.

***

# 5. Common Design Pattern (Best Practice)

### Use `unique_ptr` internally, `shared_ptr` at boundaries

```cpp
class Manager {
    std::unique_ptr<Resource> res;
public:
    Manager() : res(std::make_unique<Resource>()) {}
};
```

Convert to `shared_ptr` **only if needed**:

```cpp
std::shared_ptr<Resource> shared = std::move(uniquePtr);
```

***

# 6. Very Important Pitfall ⚠️

## Cyclic References with `shared_ptr`

```cpp
struct A {
    std::shared_ptr<B> b;
};
struct B {
    std::shared_ptr<A> a;
};
```

❌ Memory leak: reference count never reaches zero.

✅ Fix using `std::weak_ptr`:

```cpp
struct B {
    std::weak_ptr<A> a; // does not increase ref count
};
```

***

# 7. Interview‑Ready Answer ✅

> Use `std::unique_ptr` when there is a single owner and ownership can be transferred. It’s fast, safe, and should be the default.  
> Use `std::shared_ptr` only when multiple components need shared ownership and the object’s lifetime must be managed collectively.

***

# 8. Final Takeaway 🔑

*   ✅ **Prefer `unique_ptr`**
*   ✅ **Use `shared_ptr` only when ownership must be shared**
*   ✅ Avoid premature `shared_ptr`
*   ✅ Watch out for cycles (use `weak_ptr`)

